and partisan influencers). They use these technologies and strategies to create a bandwagon effect by bringing the content into parallel discussions with other legitimate users, or to mold discontent for political purposes. Drawing on eight years of original international ethnographic research among the people who build, combat, and experience these propaganda campaigns, Woolley presents an extensive view of the evolution of computational propaganda, offers a glimpse into the future, and suggests pragmatic responses for policy makers, academics, technologists, and others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aCommunication in politicsxTechnological innovations. 0aDigital mediaxPolitical aspects. 0aDisinformationxTechnological innovations. 0aPropagandaxTechnological innovations. 0aSocial mediaxPolitical aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Propaganda.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074978640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300269154?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300269154423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300269154/original  a978-3-11-074978-6  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY